{"title_page": "Henry Lewis Bullen", "text_new": "{{short description|American printer and archivist}}\n'''Henry Lewis Bullen''' (1857 \u2013 April 27, 1938) was a [[Printer (publishing)|printer]] and [[Typography|typographic]] [[archivist]].\n\n== Early life ==\nHenry Lewis Bullen was born in 1857 in [[Ballarat]], [[Australia]] to American-Scotch parentage. He left school at 14 to become a printers apprentice and began writing articles for trade publications. In 1875, he immigrated to the United States. He lived for ten years in [[Boston]] where he worked as a printer, later becoming the editor of ''Trade Review'', a printers publication, and made frequent visits to [[New York City]] to study new printing technologies.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HSFu99FCJwQC&pg=PA155&lpg=PA155&dq=%22Henry+Lewis+Bullen%22&source=bl&ots=SSEDPWSXAW&sig=Wsq1HBJSk1A2GD_8F1EE2RZVrj8&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjb5OeZxuLQAhVpxoMKHavMBrUQ6AEIXDAQ#v=onepage&q=%22Henry%20Lewis%20Bullen%22&f=false|title=World Encyclopedia of Library and Information Services|last=Wedgeworth|first=Robert|date=1993-01-01|publisher=American Library Association|isbn=9780838906095|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g_ooAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA204&lpg=PA204&dq=Henry+Lewis+Bullen&source=bl&ots=AGm1o7jXxt&sig=9ZBrx7JNwqXl6IY0ISEwco4CfZc&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwijy5flxeLQAhXJ7YMKHeqvA4I4ChDoAQgZMAA#v=onepage&q=Henry%20Lewis%20Bullen&f=false|title=The Inland and American Printer and Lithographer|date=1899-01-01|publisher=Maclean-Hunter Publishing Company|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nIn 1891, Bullen moved to New York City to work as the advertising manager for Hamilton Manufacturing Company, a printers supplier, who later became part of [[American Type Founders|The American Type Founders' Company]] (ATF). \n\nBullen experienced calamity in 1905, when he left to work at the United Printing Machinery Company. He rapidly fell out with his employer and was demoted, and then disappeared with $2750 of company money, being arrested by Pinkerton detectives with a ticket to Honolulu.<ref name=\"Statement in regard to Mr. Bullen\">{{cite journal|title=Statement in regard to Mr. Bullen|journal=The American Printer|date=1905|page=302|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=W_4gAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA302|accessdate=12 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Regarding Henry L. Bullen\">{{cite journal|title=Regarding Henry L. Bullen|journal=The Inland Printer|date=1905|page=284|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=o_0gAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA284|accessdate=12 November 2017}}</ref> He was sentenced to two years in prison (reduced from ten as a first offence). Bullen's friend Herbert Bingham suggested that he had experienced a breakdown due to overwork. Robert Nelson of ATF took pity on him and he returned to ATF in 1908.<ref name=\"Ultrabold\">{{cite journal|title=Henry Lewis Bullen|journal=Ultrabold|issue=11}}</ref>\n\nBullen became ATF's advertising manager and informal corporate historian, he was responsible for producing type specimen books, machinery and material catalogs and pamphlets. He also successfully marketed the concept of \"[[Type family|type families]],\" offering further weights than roman and italic and introduced classic revivals of [[Garamond]], [[Caslon]], [[Cloister (typeface)|Cloister]], and [[Bodoni]]. He was also a contributor to ''The Inland Printer''.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"Loxley\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9AfP2prmEDUC&pg=PA72|title=Type: The Secret History of Letters|last=Loxley|first=Simon|date=2006-06-12|publisher=I.B.Tauris|isbn=9781845110284|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAt ATF, Bullen began expanding his personal collection that would become the foundation for the ATF Library in 1908 in [[Jersey City, New Jersey|Jersey City]]. The ATF Library was \"to serve as a model of art and craftsmanship to students of typography...to memorialize or honor predecessors in our profession or printers now living...[and to] enhance the appreciation by the general public of printing as an art and influence.\"<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://exhibitions.cul.columbia.edu/exhibits/show/type_to_print/atf|title=Columbia University Libraries Online Exhibitions {{!}} Type to Print: The Book & The Type Specimen Book|website=exhibitions.cul.columbia.edu|access-date=2016-12-07}}</ref> The ATF Library merged the collections of [[Theodore Low De Vinne]], Typothethae of the City of New York and the Franklin Typographic Society along with numerous smaller collections. Bullen served as librarian and was responsible for over 16,000 documents at its peak. In 1923, he advertised help at the library while compiling the 1923 type specimen book, hiring [[Beatrice Warde]] as assistant librarian.<ref name=\"Beatrice Warde: Manners and type\">{{cite web|last1=De Bondt|first1=Sara|title=Beatrice Warde: Manners and type|url=http://www.eyemagazine.com/feature/article/beatrice-warde-manners-and-type|website=Eye Magazine|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref> He later retired that year, and traveled to Europe to acquire rare books for the library. After ATF declared bankruptcy in 1933, Bullen began talks with [[Columbia University]] to acquire the library as he felt that the library housed at the University would provide the greatest research value to the public. The ATF Library was moved to Columbia University in 1936 and opened to the public in 1939. The University officially purchased the collection in 1941.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1939/06/27/93934358.html?pageNumber=30|title=COLUMBIA DEDICATES LIBRARY OF PRINTING; Plaqae to H.L. Bullen, Founder of Collection, Unveiled|access-date=2016-12-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1942/01/11/85505879.html?pageNumber=39|title=PRINTING LIBRARY GOES TO COLUMBIA; University Acquires One of World's Famous Collections of Graphic Arts VALUE IS PUT AT $400,000 Rare Items Include Presses, Letters, Religious Books and Many Oddities|access-date=2016-12-07}}</ref>\n\nBullen also lectured on graphic arts, wrote about typography, and curated exhibitions on typography. Contemporary amateur historian of printing David M. Macmillan however has expressed concern that his writing was often inaccurate: \"I have come to the point where I find it impossible to rely upon anything that he said which does not have external corroboration.\"<ref name=\"MacMillan\">{{cite web|last1=MacMillan|first1=David|title=Henry Lewis Bullen|url=https://www.circuitousroot.com/artifice/letters/press/typemaking/history/type-scholars/bullen/index.html|website=Circuitous Root (blog)|accessdate=4 November 2017}}</ref> [[Beatrice Warde]] later in life said he had suppressed suspicions that the \"Garamond\" type his company was reviving was not really the work of sixteenth-century engraver [[Claude Garamond]], noting that he had never been able to find a sixteenth-century book that contained it; Warde discovered a few years later that it had actually been cut by the little-known [[Jean Jannon]] in the following century.<ref name=\"Loxley\" /> In 1911, he helped to found the Printers Apprentices of New York, which became a part of the [[High School of Graphic Communication Arts|New York School of Printing]].<ref name=\"timesmachine.nytimes.com\">{{Cite news|url=http://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1938/04/28/98128141.html?pageNumber=23|title=HENRY BULLEN, 80, AUTHORITY ON TYPE; Designer of Machinery and a Historian of Printing Is Dead in His Home Designed New Equipment Lectured on Graphic Arts|access-date=2016-12-07}}</ref> He was awarded the [[List of AIGA medalists|AIGA Medal]] in 1934.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.aiga.org/medal|title=AIGA Medal and Medalists|newspaper=AIGA {{!}} the professional association for design|access-date=2016-12-06}}</ref>\n\n== Death ==\nBullen died on April 27, 1938 in [[Elmhurst, Queens|Elmhurst]], [[Queens]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"timesmachine.nytimes.com\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bullen, Henry}}\n{{authority control}}\n[[Category:1857 births]]\n[[Category:1938 deaths]]\n[[Category:American printers]]\n[[Category:American archivists]]\n[[Category:People from Ballarat]]\n[[Category:Australian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:AIGA medalists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American printer and archivist}}\n'''Henry Lewis Bullen''' (1857 \u2013 April 27, 1938) was a [[Printer (publishing)|printer]] and [[Typography|typographic]] [[archivist]].\n\n== Early life ==\nHenry Lewis Bullen was born in 1857 in [[Ballarat]], [[Australia]] to American-Scotch parentage. He left school at 14 to become a printers apprentice and began writing articles for trade publications. In 1875, he immigrated to the United States. He lived for ten years in [[Boston]] where he worked as a printer, later becoming the editor of ''Trade Review'', a printers publication, and made frequent visits to [[New York City]] to study new printing technologies.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HSFu99FCJwQC&pg=PA155&lpg=PA155&dq=%22Henry+Lewis+Bullen%22&source=bl&ots=SSEDPWSXAW&sig=Wsq1HBJSk1A2GD_8F1EE2RZVrj8&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjb5OeZxuLQAhVpxoMKHavMBrUQ6AEIXDAQ#v=onepage&q=%22Henry%20Lewis%20Bullen%22&f=false|title=World Encyclopedia of Library and Information Services|last=Wedgeworth|first=Robert|date=1993-01-01|publisher=American Library Association|isbn=9780838906095|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g_ooAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA204&lpg=PA204&dq=Henry+Lewis+Bullen&source=bl&ots=AGm1o7jXxt&sig=9ZBrx7JNwqXl6IY0ISEwco4CfZc&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwijy5flxeLQAhXJ7YMKHeqvA4I4ChDoAQgZMAA#v=onepage&q=Henry%20Lewis%20Bullen&f=false|title=The Inland and American Printer and Lithographer|date=1899-01-01|publisher=Maclean-Hunter Publishing Company|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nIn 1891, Bullen moved to New York City to work as the advertising manager for Hamilton Manufacturing Company, a printers supplier, who later became part of [[American Type Founders|The American Type Founders' Company]] (ATF). \n\nBullen experienced calamity in 1905, when he left to work at the United Printing Machinery Company. He rapidly fell out with his employer and was demoted, and then disappeared with $2750 of company money, being arrested by Pinkerton detectives with a ticket to Honolulu.<ref name=\"Statement in regard to Mr. Bullen\">{{cite journal|title=Statement in regard to Mr. Bullen|journal=The American Printer|date=1905|page=302|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=W_4gAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA302|accessdate=12 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Regarding Henry L. Bullen\">{{cite journal|title=Regarding Henry L. Bullen|journal=The Inland Printer|date=1905|page=284|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=o_0gAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA284|accessdate=12 November 2017}}</ref> He was sentenced to two years in prison (reduced from ten as a first offence). Bullen's friend Herbert Bingham suggested that he had experienced a breakdown due to overwork. Robert Nelson of ATF took pity on him and he returned to ATF in 1908.<ref name=\"Ultrabold\">{{cite journal|title=Henry Lewis Bullen|journal=Ultrabold|issue=11}}</ref>\n\nBullen became ATF's advertising manager and informal corporate historian, he was responsible for producing type specimen books, machinery and material catalogs and pamphlets. He also successfully marketed the concept of \"[[Type family|type families]],\" offering further weights than roman and italic and introduced classic revivals of [[Garamond]], [[Caslon]], [[Cloister (typeface)|Cloister]], and [[Bodoni]]. He was also a contributor to ''The Inland Printer''.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"Loxley\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9AfP2prmEDUC&pg=PA72|title=Type: The Secret History of Letters|last=Loxley|first=Simon|date=2006-06-12|publisher=I.B.Tauris|isbn=9781845110284|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAt ATF, Bullen began expanding his personal collection that would become the foundation for the ATF Library in 1908 in [[Jersey City, New Jersey|Jersey City]]. The ATF Library was \"to serve as a model of art and craftsmanship to students of typography...to memorialize or honor predecessors in our profession or printers now living...[and to] enhance the appreciation by the general public of printing as an art and influence.\"<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://exhibitions.cul.columbia.edu/exhibits/show/type_to_print/atf|title=Columbia University Libraries Online Exhibitions {{!}} Type to Print: The Book & The Type Specimen Book|website=exhibitions.cul.columbia.edu|access-date=2016-12-07}}</ref> The ATF Library merged the collections of [[Theodore Low De Vinne]], Typothethae of the City of New York and the Franklin Typographic Society along with numerous smaller collections. Bullen served as librarian and was responsible for over 16,000 documents at its peak. In 1923, he advertised help at the library while compiling the 1923 type specimen book, hiring [[Beatrice Warde]] as assistant librarian.<ref name=\"Beatrice Warde: Manners and type\">{{cite web|last1=De Bondt|first1=Sara|title=Beatrice Warde: Manners and type|url=http://www.eyemagazine.com/feature/article/beatrice-warde-manners-and-type|website=Eye Magazine|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref> He later retired that year, and traveled to Europe to acquire rare books for the library. After ATF declared bankruptcy in 1933, Bullen began talks with [[Columbia University]] to acquire the library as he felt that the library housed at the University would provide the greatest research value to the public. The ATF Library was moved to Columbia University in 1936 and opened to the public in 1939. The University officially purchased the collection in 1941.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1939/06/27/93934358.html?pageNumber=30|title=COLUMBIA DEDICATES LIBRARY OF PRINTING; Plaqae to H.L. Bullen, Founder of Collection, Unveiled|access-date=2016-12-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1942/01/11/85505879.html?pageNumber=39|title=PRINTING LIBRARY GOES TO COLUMBIA; University Acquires One of World's Famous Collections of Graphic Arts VALUE IS PUT AT $400,000 Rare Items Include Presses, Letters, Religious Books and Many Oddities|access-date=2016-12-07}}</ref>\n\nBullen also lectured on graphic arts, wrote about typography, and curated exhibitions on typography. Contemporary amateur historian of printing David M. Macmillan however has expressed concern that his writing was often inaccurate: \"I have come to the point where I find it impossible to rely upon anything that he said which does not have external corroboration.\"<ref name=\"MacMillan\">{{cite web|last1=MacMillan|first1=David|title=Henry Lewis Bullen|url=https://www.circuitousroot.com/artifice/letters/press/typemaking/history/type-scholars/bullen/index.html|website=Circuitous Root (blog)|accessdate=4 November 2017}}</ref> [[Beatrice Warde]] later in life said he had suppressed suspicions that the \"Garamond\" type his company was reviving was genuinely the work of sixteenth-century engraver [[Claude Garamond]], noting that he had never been able to find a sixteenth-century book that contained it; Warde discovered a few years later that it had actually been cut by the little-known [[Jean Jannon]] in the following century.<ref name=\"Loxley\" /> In 1911, he helped to found the Printers Apprentices of New York, which became a part of the [[High School of Graphic Communication Arts|New York School of Printing]].<ref name=\"timesmachine.nytimes.com\">{{Cite news|url=http://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1938/04/28/98128141.html?pageNumber=23|title=HENRY BULLEN, 80, AUTHORITY ON TYPE; Design